  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "The six principles are phrased as high-level platitudes rather than concrete guidelines for how this role operates differently from others.",
      "example_rewrite": "• Contextual Precision: Provide exactly the project’s data schema, business rules, and stakeholder preferences so agents respond with tailored recommendations."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "No anti-patterns are defined. Without role-specific warnings, the specialist may repeat common mistakes like overloading agents with stale context or skipping human checkpoints.",
      "example_rewrite": "Anti-pattern: ‘Context Dumping’ – Injecting all historical project files without filtering, causing agents to misinterpret priorities. Instead, curate only current sprint documents and stakeholder briefs."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "Placeholders in the Context Requirements section (e.g. [Context item 1]) leave an AI agent uncertain which artifacts to gather and how to verify readiness.",
      "example_rewrite": "Required Context: • project-charter.md • sprint-backlog.csv • stakeholder-map.xlsx • compliance-checklist.pdf"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix lists deployment areas but gives no actionable steps or metrics tied to these priorities (e.g., target headcount, SLAs).",
      "example_rewrite": "Festival surge: Ramp up 30 seasonal agents with event-specific scripts within 48 hrs; track daily readiness rate ≥ 95%."
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a dedicated Anti-Pattern section with 3–5 role-specific warnings and corrective examples."
}

```json
{
  "role": "agent-onboarding-specialist",
  "department": "human-resources",
  "scores": {
    "philosophy_depth": 2,
    "handoff_specificity": 5,
    "anti_pattern_quality": 1,
    "ai_deployment_clarity": 4,
    "story_portal_relevance": 3
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "All six principles are single-phrase platitudes with one-word or two-word 'meanings' that convey nothing specific to agent onboarding. 'Ready From Day One = Fully prepared agents' is circular and meaningless. 'Smooth Onboarding = Frictionless deployment' is a tautology. None of the principles describe HOW this role thinks, what tradeoffs it navigates, or what makes onboarding in an AI workforce context uniquely challenging. Any HR onboarding role at any company could use these exact phrases.",
      "example_rewrite": "| **Context Completeness Over Speed** | A misconfigured agent that launches fast fails the project. Delay deployment until the context package includes project goals, tone guidelines, key stakeholders, and known constraints — not just a role file. | | **Role-Project Fit Is Not Optional** | Assigning a role because it exists in the registry is insufficient. Every deployment must include a documented rationale: why this role template matches this project's actual needs, not just its category. | | **Verification Means Dialogue, Not Checkbox** | Readiness is confirmed by prompting the deployed agent with real project scenarios and reviewing responses — not by confirming files were loaded. | | **Handoff Is a Transfer of Accountability** | When the agent moves to the project team, the Specialist documents what context was injected, what was omitted and why, and what edge cases were identified — so the PM inherits full situational awareness. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "Handoffs name real roles and artifact types, which is a baseline pass. However, the artifacts are vague categories rather than specific named deliverables. 'Staffing requests' does not specify what format or template. 'Deployed agents' is an outcome, not an artifact with a defined structure. 'Deployment records' does not identify what fields the Workforce Registry Manager expects. The Skill Developer handoff says 'Skill files' without specifying the file naming convention (e.g., skill-name.md) referenced elsewhere in the template. The Works With table says 'All Department Heads' which is not a specific role.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Receives From | Artifact | Format | \n|---|---|---| \n| Project Manager | Staffing Request Form (staffing-request-v1.md) — includes role categories needed, project timeline, deployment date, context documents | Standardized form | \n| Role Engineer | Role template file (role-name.md) — versioned, approved, with Classification and Deployment fields complete | Markdown file | \n| Skill Developer | Skill file (skill-name.md) — includes trigger conditions and load-when criteria | Markdown file | \n\n| Delivers To | Artifact | Format | \n|---|---|---| \n| Project Team Lead | Deployed Agent Handoff Package — includes injected context summary, readiness verification log, known gaps | PDF + registry entry | \n| Workforce Registry Manager | Deployment Record — agent ID, role file version, project assignment, deployment date, context package hash | Registry form |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no Anti-Patterns section in this role file at all. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns. The DO/DON'T boundary section exists but serves a different purpose — it defines scope, not failure modes. Anti-patterns should describe the specific ways this role goes wrong in practice: e.g., deploying an agent with a role file but no project context, confusing 'agent configured' with 'agent ready', or treating all projects as identical staffing problems.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | Why It Fails | Correct Behavior |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Deploying the closest role instead of the right role** | Assigning a role because it roughly matches wastes project time correcting behavior. | Document the specific fit rationale before deployment; escalate to Role Engineer if no template matches. |\n| **Treating context injection as file transfer** | Loading a project brief into an agent's context does not mean the agent understood it. | Run a comprehension verification dialogue with real project questions before marking deployment complete. |\n| **Marking readiness complete before STOP confirmation** | Skipping human checkpoints to accelerate deployment produces unchecked errors that surface in production. | Every STOP point in the deployment workflow requires explicit human sign-off before proceeding. |\n| **Onboarding agents without gap documentation** | Omitting what context was unavailable at deployment leaves the PM blind to agent limitations. | Every handoff package must include a 'Known Gaps' field even if the answer is 'none identified.' |\n| **Re-deploying a role template without version check** | Using a cached or outdated role file deploys stale behavior. | Confirm the role template version against the Workforce Registry before every deployment. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Context Requirements section — arguably the most critical section for an AI agent loading this role — contains only unfilled placeholder text: '[Context item 1]' and '[Context item 2]'. The Required Skills table is also empty with only a format note. This means an AI agent loading this role has no idea what project context it needs to request before starting work, and no skills to load. Additionally, the iteration protocol is generic and does not specify what a 'deployment status report' should contain, what triggers a priority change, or how the AI should handle ambiguous staffing requests. The role also lacks any first-action instruction — what should the AI do in the first 60 seconds after being deployed?",
      "example_rewrite": "### Required Context\n- [ ] Project name, type (platform / festival / community / content), and target launch date\n- [ ] List of roles requested from the Organizational Charter\n- [ ] Project Manager name and preferred communication cadence\n- [ ] Any known constraints (timeline pressure, skill gaps, restricted role categories)\n- [ ] Access to Workforce Registry for role availability check\n\n### Required Skills\n| Skill | When to Load |\n|---|---|\n| context-injection-protocol.md | Every deployment |\n| readiness-verification-checklist.md | Before every handoff |\n| staffing-conflict-escalation.md | When role availability conflict arises |\n\n### First Action on Deployment\nWhen activated, immediately request the Staffing Request Form from the initiating Project Manager. Do not begin role matching until the form is received and the project type is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 3,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix names four project types (Platform, Festival, Community, Content) but provides no actionable specifics: no role names commonly needed per project type, no timing patterns (e.g., festival surge windows), no known staffing challenges specific to Story Portal, and no registry identifiers or naming conventions. The priorities table simply restates the four categories in numbered order without explaining why platform development ranks above festival operations. A specialist loading this role for a Story Portal festival deployment would gain no concrete guidance from this section.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Story Portal Deployment Specifics\n\n| Project Type | Typical Roles Needed | Lead Time | Known Challenges |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Festival Event** | Event Coordinator Agent, Content Producer Agent, Community Manager Agent, Social Media Agent | 3 weeks pre-event | Surge volume; roles must be deployed simultaneously; festival-specific context package required |\n| **Platform Launch** | Frontend Agent, QA Agent, Technical Writer Agent, DevOps Agent | 4 weeks pre-launch | Engineering roles require code repository context injection; QA must be deployed before Frontend |\n| **Community Initiative** | Community Manager Agent, Content Producer Agent | 2 weeks pre-launch | Tone and voice guidelines are mandatory context; generic deployment produces off-brand output |\n| **Content Production** | Content Producer Agent, Editor Agent | 1 week per sprint | Sprint backlog must be injected as context at the start of each cycle; stale context is the primary failure mode |"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Complete the Context Requirements section immediately — the unfilled placeholders ('[Context item 1]', '[Context item 2]') and empty Skills table mean an AI agent loading this role cannot begin work. This is a blocking defect. Specify the exact context items required before deployment begins, the skill files to load, and add a First Action instruction so the agent knows what to do in the first 60 seconds. All other quality issues are secondary to an AI agent that cannot orient itself on activation."
}
